User Research

One of the core activities in UX is conducting user research. Research helps you refine your understanding of how users will interact with a product, what they'll think, and even what they'll feel.

# 

<span key="40e9f39ad8d5459198e5366910d91fa6"><span offset-key="40e9f39ad8d5459198e5366910d91fa6:0">User Research</span></span>

<span key="9c0528462ec94c4a8af0e6c7bc9f8b5e"><span offset-key="9c0528462ec94c4a8af0e6c7bc9f8b5e:0">One of the core activities in UX is conducting user research. Research helps you refine your understanding of how users will interact with a product, what they'll think, and even what they'll </span>*feel*<span offset-key="9c0528462ec94c4a8af0e6c7bc9f8b5e:2">.</span></span>

<span key="ccef1174f9854f569989815efdf55ce1"><span offset-key="ccef1174f9854f569989815efdf55ce1:0">The idea that we should focus on what users are </span>*feeling*<span offset-key="ccef1174f9854f569989815efdf55ce1:2"> when they're using our product might strike you as weird or silly, but it's actually </span>*the ultimate way*<span offset-key="ccef1174f9854f569989815efdf55ce1:4"> to zero in on building the right thing. If users enjoy using your product, they'll use it often, maybe purchase it if that's the business model, tell their friends about it, write epic poems about it...</span></span>

<span key="b1237a592bc54dea850272f13771be1f"><span offset-key="b1237a592bc54dea850272f13771be1f:0">When users use a product, they're constantly making both conscious and unconscious observations about their experience:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="12bb0b82ca894327864908f7d36f8bbe"><span offset-key="12bb0b82ca894327864908f7d36f8bbe:0">"This is </span>*frustrating*<span offset-key="12bb0b82ca894327864908f7d36f8bbe:2">â€”I'm trying to go back, but I can't!"</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9c27cc9779fc4d8d84793c59e93b7e18"><span offset-key="9c27cc9779fc4d8d84793c59e93b7e18:0">"This is </span>*so neat*<span offset-key="9c27cc9779fc4d8d84793c59e93b7e18:2">â€”I can slide here and see the graph change right away!"</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b3dfe7339f3c4f829b7a912a0c19e5b5"><span offset-key="b3dfe7339f3c4f829b7a912a0c19e5b5:0">"I really </span>*wish*<span offset-key="b3dfe7339f3c4f829b7a912a0c19e5b5:2"> I could see that other table right next to this one to compare them directly."</span></span>

<span key="a1fb0745fb174281993fda699cf8d2cc"><span offset-key="a1fb0745fb174281993fda699cf8d2cc:0">We should always try to </span>*anticipate*<span offset-key="a1fb0745fb174281993fda699cf8d2cc:2"> how our users will experience our productâ€”but ultimately, </span>*we'll never be able to anticipate everything*<span offset-key="a1fb0745fb174281993fda699cf8d2cc:4">. That's why user research can be so usefulâ€”it lets us cheat by getting more information!</span></span>

## 

<span key="ad9e5c1a23d24b799b956bf9bbfe715b"><span offset-key="ad9e5c1a23d24b799b956bf9bbfe715b:0">User Research Methods</span></span>

<span key="25bd729ec17c416193090fd39e242bce"><span offset-key="25bd729ec17c416193090fd39e242bce:0">Let's say you're working on a product that lets homebuyers shop and apply for a mortgage. How would you conduct some user research to point you in the right direction?</span></span>

### 

<span key="50fc76466b7b4d82a938f4808e8d3ebf"><span offset-key="50fc76466b7b4d82a938f4808e8d3ebf:0">Discovery</span></span>

<span key="0560adfcbc974aa1a869a0cef4a2a02f">**Discovery**<span offset-key="0560adfcbc974aa1a869a0cef4a2a02f:1"> is usually the first step in UX design research. It focuses on finding or generating some initial information to get oriented about a problem space and the people facing those problems.</span></span>

<span key="46381482515a4359ad49eacf246df0ff"><span offset-key="46381482515a4359ad49eacf246df0ff:0">Discovery is broad and often purposefully open-ended; you're just trying to figure out: "what's going on here?"</span></span>

<span key="27944caaf2264079ab2bae36e8fd0ed4"><span offset-key="27944caaf2264079ab2bae36e8fd0ed4:0">Common tools for discovery include:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4800136a5ca848169c2a07d10d460308">**reading**<span offset-key="4800136a5ca848169c2a07d10d460308:1"> articles and studies (e.g., about the housing market, the mortgage lending industry, public policy...)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9e30985f50924c0ba759ea733b2d8f25">**interviewing**<span offset-key="9e30985f50924c0ba759ea733b2d8f25:1"> people facing a problem you're interested in solving with your product (e.g., recent, active, or potential homebuyers) or people adjacent to those problems (e.g., interviewing someone working for a mortgage lender to learn more about the mortgage application process)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0f111963fdbd40a2920c781b1996d2f1">**holding workshops**<span offset-key="0f111963fdbd40a2920c781b1996d2f1:1"> with various combinations of stakeholder groups (</span>**stakeholder:**<span offset-key="0f111963fdbd40a2920c781b1996d2f1:3"> anyone with a "stake" in the development process)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="d8f5cc90180d4b4cab1bb19cf4c0b675">**gathering data**<span offset-key="d8f5cc90180d4b4cab1bb19cf4c0b675:1"> (e.g., from real mortgage applications)</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="e39302618a5d41d58550b64d122b81a1">**taking notes**<span offset-key="e39302618a5d41d58550b64d122b81a1:1"> based on your own experiences (e.g., applying for a mortgage)</span></span>

### 

<span key="7138fd628d604ce986308fe04034d24c"><span offset-key="7138fd628d604ce986308fe04034d24c:0">Exploration</span></span>

<span key="42d9750f57b249768fa03cfc6524fc8a">**Exploration**<span offset-key="42d9750f57b249768fa03cfc6524fc8a:1"> is a bit less open-ended than discovery, and involves actually diving into the information you've generated.</span></span>

<span key="df644491de5b46129308eec56d998cc5"><span offset-key="df644491de5b46129308eec56d998cc5:0">Usually, a major goal of the exploration process is </span>**feature mapping**<span offset-key="df644491de5b46129308eec56d998cc5:2">â€”linking the user needs you've identified to potential features to build in your product.</span></span>

<span key="5a1d63cb430e4b82babb5809a5895a59"><span offset-key="5a1d63cb430e4b82babb5809a5895a59:0">Common tools for exploration include:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b081f1be18584dc1bc382d02cb7f8af2">**defining personas**<span offset-key="b081f1be18584dc1bc382d02cb7f8af2:1"> of representative groups of potential users based on the data you've got (e.g., "Thomas is a 41-year-old bitcoin miner with a credit score of...")</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="e055c39fc0ae415c94d63124c0fbd291">**drafting user stories**<span offset-key="e055c39fc0ae415c94d63124c0fbd291:1"> (which you'll do in Labs!) to put yourself in the perspective of your users for each action they'll need to take to solve their problems (e.g., "As a user, I can specify a desired APR and see how much I'd have to pay in points to get that rate.")</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="cad88a2839ec45e9a7ee8b1f43659c47">**prototyping**<span offset-key="cad88a2839ec45e9a7ee8b1f43659c47:1"> early ideas for key areas of your product, possibly interactive (e.g., a clickable mockup of a rate comparison page)</span></span>

### 

<span key="5d9943d2f92c49169f0c7f1f3bcfe9f5"><span offset-key="5d9943d2f92c49169f0c7f1f3bcfe9f5:0">Testing & Feedback</span></span>

<span key="f74cb117bd4e44819ea160d7ad5e9016">**Testing**<span offset-key="f74cb117bd4e44819ea160d7ad5e9016:1"> is checking the performance of your application with specific metrics in mind; </span>**feedback**<span offset-key="f74cb117bd4e44819ea160d7ad5e9016:3"> is putting something in front of users to see how they react and/or what they say about their experience.</span></span>

<span key="a0ef3567b87a404f89ad7c879d12795d"><span offset-key="a0ef3567b87a404f89ad7c879d12795d:0">Common tools for testing & feedback include:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4b4892de0e0748a1a27069f5f6ad0429">**usability testing**<span offset-key="4b4892de0e0748a1a27069f5f6ad0429:1"> to see what users say about how easy it was to accomplish their goals (e.g., "I felt like it look a lot of clicks to get to the part where I could finally view the rates.")</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9eff398d7aaf4ba5962e86a780907eb1">**deploying heatmaps**<span offset-key="9eff398d7aaf4ba5962e86a780907eb1:1"> to see where users move their mouse, click, or even </span>*look*<span offset-key="9eff398d7aaf4ba5962e86a780907eb1:3"> while using a version of your product (e.g., "Wow, look how much red is over the rate comparison button! We're really driving users effectively toward taking that primary action.")</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="73396648012d441ba70d857ff46adef1">**user surveys**<span offset-key="73396648012d441ba70d857ff46adef1:1"> to gather any other qualitative information (e.g., "How clear were the visualizations of interest rates over time?")</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="24a6145bb4234040881b39e28af4dc6e">**analytics**<span offset-key="24a6145bb4234040881b39e28af4dc6e:1"> for a deployed product (e.g., the number of daily active users (DAU))</span></span>

<span key="65a8e5bd395f4108ac0f5f81a085b3e8"><span offset-key="65a8e5bd395f4108ac0f5f81a085b3e8:0">Use these methods based on your best determination of when and with whom they'll be most relevant, based on the context, timeline, and goals of your product.</span></span>
